    <div xml:id="PN368">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>kaḷiṟu mukantu peyarkuva meṉiṉē</l>
<l>yoḷiṟumaḻai tavirkkuṅ  kuṉṟam pōlak</l>
<l>kaimmā vellāṅ kaṇaiyiṭat tolaintaṉa</l>
<l>koṭuñci neṭuntēr mukakkuva meṉiṉē</l>
<l>kaṭumpari naṉmāṉ vāṅkuvayi ṉolki</l>
<l>neṭumpī ṭaḻintu nilañcērn taṉavē</l>
<l>koycuvaṟ puravi mukakkuva meṉiṉē</l>
<l>meyniṟainta vaḻuvoṭu perumpiṟi tāki</l>
<l>vaḷivaḻak kaṟutta vaṅkam pōlak</l>
<l>kuruti yamperum puṉalkūrntaṉavē</l>
<l>yāṅka, mukavai yiṉmaiyi ṉukavai yiṉṟi</l>
<l>yirappō riraṅku <supplied>mi</supplied>ṉṉā viyaṉkaḷat</l>
<l>tāḷaḻip paṭutta vāḷē ruḻava</l>
<l>kaṭāa yāṉai kālvaḻi yaṉṉavaṉ</l>
<l>ṟeṭārit teṇkaṇ ṭeḷirppa voṟṟip</l>
<l>pāṭi vanta tellāṅ kōṭiyar</l>
<l>muḻavumaru ṟirumaṇi miṭaintaniṉ</l>
<l>ṉaravuṟa ḻāra mukakkuva meṉavē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>If we were to come back after bringing in elephant bulls, (1)</l>
<l>like hills that retain bright clouds (2)</l>
<l>all [those] hand animals would be lost when arrows were put [into them]. (3)</l>
<l>If we were to draw in tall chariots with support staffs, (4)</l>
<l>the fast-moving fine horses becoming weary on the curved side, (5)</l>
<l>[their] long pride perishing they would join the ground. (6)</l>
<l>If we were to draw in horses with trimmed manes, (7)</l>
<l>with scars that fill [their] bodies, encountering the great other, (8)</l>
<l>like ships when the movement of the wind is cut off, (9)</l>
<l>they would fill a great flood of blood. Thus, (10)</l>
<l>In the absence of things to bring in, without things that drop, (11)</l>
<l>on the unpleasant wide field where those who beg are aggrieved, (12)</l>
<l>o you ploughman who ploughs with a sword that destroys men, (13)</l>
<l>loudly beating the clear eye of my Teṭāri drum (15)</l>
<l>that is like the way of a rutting elephant’s foot (14)</l>
<l>singing came all the dancers, (16)</l>
<l>thinking “we will draw upon your snake-like strings (18)</l>
<l>that is set close with brilliant gems [large] as drums. (17)</l>
</lg>
